article.headline: Iowa State 68, Louisiana-Monroe 40
article.story: AMES, Iowa (AP) -- A little film study did wonders for Iowa State. On Saturday morning, first-year coach Greg McDermott showed his players tape from their 69-61 victory over UC Riverside the night before. A few hours later, they responded with an outstanding effort on defense in beating Louisiana-Monroe 68-40 in the second of three rounds in the Cyclone Challenge. "We felt there were too many mistakes that we made," McDermott said. "I really felt if the guys saw them on film and saw themselves in action, they'd slap themselves in the head and say, `What am I doing?' "I think that was time well spent." That it was. Mike Taylor scored 15 points and Iowa State took control with a 20-0 run spanning halftime. Wesley Johnson added 11 points and 12 rebounds for the Cyclones (2-0), who held Louisiana-Monroe to 27.3 percent shooting (15-for-55) and outrebounded the Warhawks 48-27. "We saw how we had to play," Johnson said. "We had to come out with more energy, with more intensity, and we came out like that." Louisiana-Monroe (1-1) led 17-16 after Jonas Brown's free throw with 6:46 left in the first half, but the Warhawks went the next 10:44 without a point. Iowa State closed the half with 11 straight points, then scored the first nine of the second half to open a 36-17 lead. Jordan Payne's jump shot ended the Warhawks' drought with 16:02 remaining, but they never challenged again. The Warhawks rarely got easy shots inside and they went just 3-for-22 from 3-point range after making 13 3s in a victory over Eastern Illinois on Friday night. Tony Hooper and Darien Bynum led the Warhawks with eight points apiece. "We focused pretty much on getting a hand on the shooter's shoulder," Iowa State's Corey McIntosh said. "If they want to take tough shots, we're going to make them as tough as possible. If they make them, they make them." The Cyclones big run got its start from an unlikely source. With the shot clock about to expire, Ross Marsden had to put up a 3-point shot, the first of the 6-foot-10 sophomore's career, and he made it. Taylor banked in a long jumper from out front and McIntosh brought the crowd to its feet when he caught an outlet pass from Johnson, whipped the ball behind his back on his way to the basket and took it in for a layup. McIntosh's fadeaway in the lane made it 27-17 at halftime. The 17 points were the fewest Iowa State has allowed in a half since Arkansas-Pine Bluff managed only 15 against the Cyclones on Dec. 31, 2002. "We don't have much of an inside presence," Louisiana-Monroe coach Orlando Early said. "If we don't make 3-pointers, we're in trouble." Iowa State had two 7-0 runs in building a 16-8 lead. Louisiana-Monroe answered with nine straight points to edge in front, but Marsden made his 3-pointer 36 seconds later, and the Cyclones were on their way. Just don't look for Marsden to shoot from out there again. "Ross is leading the country in 3-point field goal percentage," McDermott said with a smile, "and he's probably going to stay that way." Things went so well that the Cyclones even connected on a lob pass after failing on several attempts in their two exhibition games and against UC Riverside. McIntosh lofted the ball near the basket to Johnson, who caught it and jammed it through in one motion to make it 57-32. "At halftime, I was telling coach it was open," Johnson said. "Corey saw me and he threw it."
